	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>RushJet1</b> [ Wed Dec 17, 2008 9:51 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">bucky o'hare wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Although I'd like to add that any moments that 'don't sound' Mega Man like to me, is just me being as hairsplitting as possible.</div>
<br />
<br />Not really, the thing is that if I were to make a new Mega Man soundtrack for NES (like this one), I'd kind of combine old with new, which is what I was going for.  I didn't like that the real MM9 soundtrack <em>only</em> used old instruments to do its stuff mostly, but then for a couple parts (like wily final boss, some stuff in jewel man with <em>really</em> weird high notes) it sounded nothing like Mega Man.  I tried to make it a bit less jagged than that.. I mean every Mega Man game had its own style and the music changed over the years (MM6 sounds nothing like MM2 to me).  So when you say that there are moments that don't sound like Mega Man to you and that you're being nitpicky, you really aren't <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />  I could list off a few, like the second half of tornado man, part of galaxy man you mentioned, concrete man itself (teckkkkno), etc.
<br />
<br />As for the progress of this, since I recovered the files, I've done lots of touch-up work on most songs, and I've changed a couple parts that seemed awkward... more to come later.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


